<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between New Zealand and French Sauvignon Blanc?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">New Zealand Sauvignon Blanc, particularly from Marlborough, showcases intense tropical fruit flavors like passion fruit and gooseberry with pronounced herbaceous notes from higher levels of methoxypyrazines. French Sauvignon Blanc from Loire Valley regions like Sancerre and Pouilly-Fumé tends to be more mineral-driven and restrained, with citrus and flint characteristics from limestone-rich soils. The cooler French climate produces wines with higher acidity and more subtle fruit expression compared to New Zealand's bold, fruit-forward style.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Sauvignon Blanc good for wine beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sauvignon Blanc is excellent for beginners because of its straightforward, expressive character and food-friendly acidity. The grape's naturally high acidity and pronounced aromatics make it easy to identify flavor components like citrus, grass, and tropical fruits, helping new wine drinkers develop their palate. Unlike complex reds or oaked whites, most Sauvignon Blancs are meant to be enjoyed young and fresh, eliminating concerns about aging or decanting.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How can you tell if a Sauvignon Blanc is high quality?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">High-quality Sauvignon Blanc displays balanced acidity that's refreshing but not harsh, with clear varietal character that reflects its terroir rather than just generic citrus notes. Look for wines with good length on the palate, where flavors persist after swallowing, and aromatic complexity that goes beyond simple fruit—such as mineral notes in Loire Valley bottles or herbaceous complexity in premium New Zealand examples. Quality producers will also show vintage variation and distinct regional characteristics rather than formulaic, mass-produced flavors.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What temperature should you serve Sauvignon Blanc?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve Sauvignon Blanc at 45-50°F (7-10°C) to preserve its crisp acidity and aromatic intensity. This temperature range allows the wine's volatile compounds like thiols and methoxypyrazines to express properly without being muted by excessive cold. If served too warm (above 55°F), the wine will taste flabby and lose its refreshing character, while over-chilling below 40°F will suppress the delicate aromatics that make Sauvignon Blanc distinctive.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibeled text-wine-700 mb-2">Should you age Sauvignon Blanc or drink it young?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Most Sauvignon Blancs are best consumed within 2-3 years of vintage to enjoy their signature fresh, vibrant character. The exception is premium examples from Bordeaux (like Pessac-Léognan) and top Loire Valley producers, which can develop complex honeyed and mineral notes over 5-10 years. However, the majority of Sauvignon Blancs, especially from New World regions, are crafted to showcase immediate fruit and herbaceous qualities that diminish with extended cellaring.</p>
